       SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm) is a cryptographic hash function with a
       160 bit output.

       _S_H_A_1_(_) computes the SHA-1 message digest of the nn bytes at dd and places
       it in mmdd (which must have space for SHA_DIGEST_LENGTH == 20 bytes of
       output). If mmdd is NULL, the digest is placed in a static array.

       The following functions may be used if the message is not completely
       stored in memory:

       _S_H_A_1___I_n_i_t_(_) initializes a SSHHAA__CCTTXX structure.

       _S_H_A_1___U_p_d_a_t_e_(_) can be called repeatedly with chunks of the message to be
       hashed (lleenn bytes at ddaattaa).

       _S_H_A_1___F_i_n_a_l_(_) places the message digest in mmdd, which must have space for
       SHA_DIGEST_LENGTH == 20 bytes of output, and erases the SSHHAA__CCTTXX.

       Applications should use the higher level functions _E_V_P___D_i_g_e_s_t_I_n_i_t(3)
       etc. instead of calling the hash functions directly.

       The predecessor of SHA-1, SHA, is also implemented, but it should be
       used only when backward compatibility is required.

